export const batch170 = {
  'the-book-of-five-rings.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-book-of-five-rings', title: 'The Book of Five Rings', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781608422378 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A single life demands a single path',
        text: "Have you ever stood at a crossroads and felt unsure which direction to take? Life offers many paths. Some chase spiritual peace, while others devote themselves to medicine or craft. Most people, in the end, are searching for a skill or a passion that grows into a full way of living.\n\nIn seventeenth century Japan, swordplay was never just a sport. It was the soul of a warrior, and a true fighter had to master both the body and the spirit. From years of duels, Miyamoto Musashi developed a Way of Strategy. His ideas went far beyond the battlefield, reaching into how a person should think and live.\n\nLive by rules you set, but borrow wisdom from those who came before you.\n\nReal victory begins when you stop chasing surface tricks and start seeing the deeper rules that govern any field. Musashi's path is split into five rings, each one sharpening a different part of the warrior. The rings are called Ground, Water, Fire, Wind, and Void.\n\nSkip anything that does not serve your goal.\n\nThis summary walks you through the foundations of Musashi's thinking. You will see how a sword master from another age still has something to teach about focus, flexibility, and courage in modern life."
      },
      {
        title: 'No struggle, no growth',
        text: "The first ring, Ground, covers three big areas: discipline, sword technique, and the ability to adapt. These are the basic tools you need before you can walk the path of strategy in any part of life.\n\nStart with discipline. A warrior who cannot focus will rarely win. When your eyes lock on the target, you tend to hit it, but the moment your mind wanders to the noise around you, your accuracy drops. The lesson is simple: learn to silence distractions and train the same moves over and over until they feel natural.\n\nVictory is built in the boring hours of practice.\n\nThe second building block is using the right tool for the moment. A fighter who only knows one kind of sword is easy to read. Learning to fight with one hand gives you freedom, and it also lets you swap weapons as the situation shifts.\n\nDo not marry a single weapon. A short blade shines in tight spaces, while a long blade rules the open field. Even the sharpest steel is wasted if you draw it at the wrong moment. Timing, like technique, has to be drilled until it lives in your muscles.\n\nThe third block is flexibility. No two fights look the same, and a rigid plan usually fails. A baker cannot make bread from ground beef, and a swordsman should not charge an archer at close range. Flexibility is the art of adjusting on the fly.\n\nThese three lessons travel far past the old battlefield. You can borrow them to smooth out your closest relationships, too. Practice patience, kindness, and a calm tone until they feel natural, since no one is a perfect partner on day one. Pick the right moment to bring up hard topics, because a partner who is exhausted or anxious will not hear you well. Look for solutions where both of you win, such as offering a quiet massage after a long workday instead of dragging them to a movie."
      },
      {
        title: 'The flow of water',
        text: "The Water Ring leans into the technical side of fighting. Water is the symbol of flow and bending. Just as a river slips past every rock in its path, a true strategist finds a way around every obstacle, in combat and in daily life.\n\nTo move like water, you need a few skills working together. First, train your mind to stay calm in peacetime, so you are ready when storms arrive. A steady inner life is the foundation of a steady hand. Second, watch the bond between mind and body. If your body goes slack, your spirit softens, and the reverse is also true. Regular physical training sharpens discipline, while long hours on the couch leave you heavy and slow. Third, train your peripheral vision. Your eyes reveal what your enemy plans, so keep them open and unreadable. A rival who cannot tell where you are looking cannot predict your next move.\n\nToday's win over yesterday's self is the only fight that truly matters.\n\nThe Water Ring also covers the cuts and footwork of a real duel. One famous technique, called the Red Leaves Cut, mimics falling leaves as it knocks an opponent's blade aside. The name comes from the soft, drifting motion of withered leaves. Such moves reward fluidity in body and spirit.\n\nYour life is yours to shape, so make it shine.\n\nRemember that water can swell from a trickle into a storm at sea. In the same way, a fighter who has mastered sword, spirit, and body can move from beating a single opponent in a duel to facing down a crowd. The basics carry the weight when the numbers grow."
      },
      {
        title: 'Meet force with force',
        text: "Training matters in a one-on-one duel and in a crowded battlefield. The only way to get ready for a real fight, though, is to step into the ring. A padded practice room, no matter how many books you read in it, cannot imitate the chaos of the real thing. The Fire strategy fits any moment you feel afraid to act. The cure for fear is simple, and that is plunging into the moment.\n\nThree core principles guide you when the enemy is real, whether that enemy is a person or a problem. Awareness helps you read the shape of the fight. Application turns what you know into action. Adaptation helps you handle the moves you did not see coming.\n\nUse the world around you. Watch what helps you and what hurts you, then shift to match it. Standing with the sun at your back can blind a daytime foe, and taking the high ground turns gravity into a tool. Every edge you find complicates the battle for the other side.\n\nYou cannot learn the sea by sitting on the shore, so set sail and see what the water teaches.\n\nA real winner takes the lead instead of reacting. Change tactics when the scene changes, and play by your own rules whenever you can. The fighter who writes the rules usually wins the round.\n\nThis strategy works in modern life, where the world shifts faster than ever. You can borrow Fire principles at work. Stay current in your field, and aim to know more than the people around you. Grab hard projects the moment they appear, even if they scare you. Stay awake and alert in meetings, and your managers will notice the spark. The headline from a 2023 Collector piece compared Musashi to Bruce Lee for their shared philosophy of moving past surface tricks to find the real rules."
      },
      {
        title: 'Read the rival',
        text: "The Way of Strategy is different from other sword schools because it never bets on a single weapon or a single style. The Wind Book is a warning about over-training in one direction while ignoring the rest. A school that only teaches the short sword will crumble when a longer blade enters the room. A school that only trains the body will lose to one that trains the spirit as well.\n\nThe lesson cuts deep. Skill and attitude weigh more than muscle on the battlefield. Any training plan that ignores one side of the fight is a brittle plan. Build complex, well rounded drills that mix body, blade, and mind.\n\nStudy the rival. To beat a strategy, you need to see it clearly. Watch their habits, predict their next move, and position yourself one step ahead. Be careful, because a strong prediction can also shake your nerve. A calm mind and steady practice keep that balance in your favor.\n\nLearn about others to learn about yourself.\n\nMusashi also covers the role of speed. Speed alone is not a strategy, but it shapes the way you hold yourself in a fight. The terrain matters too. A swamp slows the feet and changes the timing. A warrior always has to weigh what the ground gives and what it takes away.\n\nIn the end, leaning on one tool or one habit is not enough. The Way of Strategy asks you to grow many skills and to carry many tools, since you never know which one the day will need. Read the rival, study the ground, and stay curious. That blend is what carries you through a real fight, and a real life."
      },
      {
        title: 'The space behind emptiness',
        text: "The last ring is the Book of the Void. For Musashi, emptiness was a doorway to a clearer spirit, a way to find the wisdom and restraint that mark a true fighter. The idea goes deeper than the page, dipping into Buddhist thought, where the Void is the truest face of reality. Everything you see is empty, and you are the one who paints meaning onto it. That is why two people can stand in the same room and walk away with very different stories.\n\nMany readers feel they cannot grasp this part, but the gap is smaller than it looks. When you finally see the Way of Strategy, whether through plain sense or through Buddhist study, you start to notice that everything sits in its proper place.\n\nTo win now, stay fully in the present.\n\nA warrior's mind has to stay clear and free of clutter. A single aim should fill the head, and that aim is to cut down the enemy in front of you. Any other thought, any plan for after the fight, only smudges your focus. Long practice makes the body move on instinct, so the mind can stay clean even when the scene shifts.\n\nThe Void is rooted in Eastern thought, yet it still speaks to modern life. Knowing that every event is colored by the viewer makes it easier to accept what life hands you, because long grudges dissolve once you see the other side. Staying in the present moment, free of spinning worries, helps you meet any challenge, and that is the heart of meditation. Repeating one skill until it becomes second nature is the path to mastery, so keep going without chasing a result, because the chase itself often kills the joy of the work."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "To Musashi, a true warrior of his age was someone who walked the Way of Strategy. Today's fighter carries a pen, not a blade, and the duels take place in meeting rooms, family kitchens, and quiet evenings at home. The stakes are just as real. The same principles that guided a samurai in the 1600s still work, four centuries later, because the human mind has not changed.\n\nTry this. Pick one activity and give it ninety focused minutes a day for ninety days. Within three months, you will see clear progress in that skill. Add a short meditation or breathing practice to settle the mind. Move the body every day, and yoga is a gentle way to keep your strength for the long race against time.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-conscious-closet.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-conscious-closet', title: 'The Conscious Closet', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781607178327 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The real price of fashion is larger than the tag',
        text: "When you picture the most profitable industries in the world, you probably think of cars, entertainment, or oil. The clothing industry belongs on that list. Worth about two and a half trillion dollars, it accounts for roughly three percent of the global economy. Add in every person who touches a garment along the way, and the number of lives involved is staggering.\n\nFor all that money, the industry leaves a heavy mark on the planet. Water runs polluted, toxic chemicals seep into soil, and carbon piles into the air. Many of the workers who sew these clothes sit in low paid factories in faraway countries, in places often labeled sweatshops.\n\nFast fashion feeds a throwaway habit. We wear an item once or twice, the trend moves on, and the piece lands in the trash. The answer sits with the buyer.\n\nEven knowing all of this, most shoppers keep filling carts and tossing bags without a second thought. Hardly anyone pauses to weigh the planet when they pick up a new shirt. Nobody wants to feel guilty for wanting to look good.\n\nWhen you buy a new pair of jeans or a fresh t-shirt, the trail behind it is invisible. You do not see the factory, the wage, or the water bill. Still, you can choose to learn more and shift the way you shop.\n\nIf you want to help the planet without giving up on style, this summary is a starting line. From building a small, sharp wardrobe to earning a little cash from the clothes you no longer wear, the ideas in The Conscious Closet are a friend to both the earth and the people who love fashion."
      },
      {
        title: 'Build a fresh wardrobe from pieces you actually love',
        text: "How many items hang in your closet that you never reach for? Maybe a shirt waits in the back, hoping to fit again someday. Maybe a pair of shoes sits in case the mood returns. Maybe something is kept just in case. That mindset is past its welcome, and the time to build a conscious wardrobe is now.\n\nA closet clearout is tough, and you have to be honest with yourself. You can do this.\n\nElizabeth Cline recommends sorting by season, because clothes sell faster when they match the current weather. Old winter coats in July gather dust, while the same coats in November find a home in minutes.\n\nThe clearout is not about losing the pieces you love. It is about learning how to shop from now on. If an item brings you joy, keep it, even if you wear it only a few times a year. If an item makes you feel flat or itchy, let it go. For the in between pieces, give them one more season before the final call.\n\nSentimental pieces belong in protective covers, stored somewhere safe. They stay clean, they stay ready, and they do not crowd the daily closet. Pull them out when you want them.\n\nPay attention to the items you reach for first. Notice how they make you feel and ask yourself why. That answer is a compass for the next shopping trip, and it helps you skip the fad buys that never quite fit your life.\n\nA clearout is also a chance to mend. Pull out the sewing kit for the small fixes, or hand the bigger repairs to a tailor. A small stitch today can save a piece from the trash tomorrow."
      },
      {
        title: 'Take charge of where your old clothes end up',
        text: "Once the clearout is done, a heap of clothes sits waiting for a new home. Resist the urge to dump it in the trash. Instead, sort the pile by where each piece should go.\n\nMany people assume that a thrift store is the right stop for everything. The idea sounds kind, since the clothes should help someone else. In practice, the trail is not always clean. Many donated bundles get shipped abroad, often to Africa, and a large share arrives too worn to sell. Those pieces end up dumped or burned, which is the opposite of a kindness.\n\nA clearout is a good moment to make a quiet promise to yourself. The next purchase will come with more thought.\n\nSend each item to the right next stop. Donate the pieces that are clean and still wearable, since they will find a new owner fast. Sell or trade the items that carry a real value, especially the in season styles. Mend the pieces with a small tear or a loose button, and they can rejoin the donation pile. Recycle the rest, the items that no one can wear or fix.\n\nSorting takes an extra few minutes, but the payoff is real. A shirt may end up on someone else's back, or its fibers may become part of a new product. Either way, it stays out of the landfill.\n\nA fun fact: eBay is one of the most common resale sites for old clothes. In 2020 alone, the platform reported a net profit of more than ten billion dollars."
      },
      {
        title: 'Match the drop off spot to the condition of the clothes',
        text: "Plenty of people still want to give their old clothes to a thrift store or a charity bin, and that impulse is generous. A little homework goes a long way, though, because not every donation lands where you hope.\n\nIf a charity catches your eye, take a few minutes to learn more. Sites like Charity Navigator list how groups spend their money and what causes they support, which helps you match your values to your giving.\n\nClothing bins are another common sight on the sidewalk, yet some of them are run by for profit collectors. The label on the bin usually tells you who is collecting, and a quick search tells you where the clothes end up. A bin with no clear name is a reason to walk on by.\n\nIf you want to know exactly where your clothes land, drop them off in person. A homeless shelter, a crisis center, or a local church group can put a warm coat to work the same day.\n\nBefore any drop off, give the clothes a quick wash and check the pockets. Tie the laces of any shoes together so they do not get separated, and patch the tiny tears or loose buttons so the new owner gets a piece that is ready to wear.\n\nSelling is another route, and it works for the best pieces in the pile. eBay and Poshmark are common resale sites, though the prices move with the season. Check what similar items sold for in the last few weeks before you set a price, and stick to in season styles for the fastest sale.\n\nFor the items that will not bring much money, the options stay open. Donate, recycle, or turn them into cleaning rags at home. Elizabeth Cline reminds readers that nothing has to be wasted, because there is always a next stop."
      },
      {
        title: 'Shop with care and build a wardrobe that works hard',
        text: "With a clean closet, the items left behind are the ones you truly love. From this point on, every purchase deserves a beat of thought, so the closet does not slide back into a clutter.\n\nThe goal is simple. Buy fewer pieces, choose well, and let them last. Each item earns its keep over years, not weeks, and that habit trims waste while saving money.\n\nBuy less, choose well, make it last.\n\nA clutter free closet leaves no room for impulse buys, which sounds easy until the marketing hits. Ad campaigns are built to convince you that you need the next thing. You usually do not.\n\nBuying less is a quiet vote for sustainable fashion. According to Wrap UK, wearing a single piece for nine months longer than you usually would cut its water, waste, and carbon impact by up to thirty percent. That is a big return for a small change.\n\nMindful shopping is good for the planet, supports better brands, and saves real money over time.\n\nTry a shopping fast. Set a window, a month, a season, anything that fits, and ask a friend to join you. The two of you can steer each other away from shop windows and toward a coffee instead. The first week is the hardest, and a clear reason for the fast keeps you honest when the sales start calling.\n\nEvery new piece from this point should earn a place in a small, sharp capsule wardrobe. Each item should mix and match with several others, so a handful of clothes creates dozens of looks."
      },
      {
        title: 'Brands that care about people and the planet',
        text: "A growing number of brands design with the planet in mind. They cut waste, treat workers fairly, and avoid the worst of the industry's footprint. Finding them takes a little digging, because the loudest marketing does not always come from the most responsible makers.\n\nA solid first step is to look closely at the clothes you already buy. Check the seams, test the zips, and feel the soles. The little details tell you a lot about how long a piece will last, and they help you build a sharper capsule wardrobe over time.\n\nSales and discount signs are a trap. Try looking at the item first and the price second, so a money off tag does not cloud your judgment. Cheap rarely means well made, and a bargain that falls apart after two washes was never a bargain.\n\nChoosing responsible brands is a good move, though no brand is perfect. The point is to support the companies that are trying to do better, even when they still have room to grow.\n\nA few tools can help. The Good on You app rates brands on sustainability and ethics, which makes the first search a lot faster. Bloggers who focus on slow fashion are another good source, and following a few of them adds a steady stream of honest reviews.\n\nIf a favorite brand falls short, speak up. A polite email about your concerns is a good first step, because companies listen to the customers they want to keep.\n\nThe pull of trends is real, and the fear of being left behind is even stronger. The fix is simple. If a piece does not fit or flatter, pass on it, no matter how loud the trend. The best wardrobe is one that makes you feel good and treads lightly on the planet at the same time."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "Caring for the planet is something everyone can join, and it goes well beyond recycling plastic or turning down the heat. The clothing industry is a giant machine, and it shows no signs of slowing down. Smarter shopping, along with support for brands that try to do the right thing, can start to bend the curve.\n\nMost closets are full of items that never get worn, and that is nothing to be ashamed of. The choice is yours. You can keep adding fad pieces that collect dust, or you can take a more thoughtful route.\n\nStart with a big clearout and notice the lift in your step. From there, donate or recycle what no longer serves you. Sell the best pieces and let someone else enjoy them, while a little extra cash lands in your pocket. The real win is keeping usable clothes out of the landfill.\n\nIf many of us follow Elizabeth Cline's advice, we will look great and do right by the planet at the same time.\n\nTry this. Set aside a day to pull every item out of your closet, queue up some music, and sort through the lot. Make a list of your favorite charities and learn how to donate to them directly. If sewing is not your strong suit, search YouTube for a quick fix, since a loose button is a small problem with a small solution.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-cult-of-we.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-cult-of-we', title: 'The Cult of We', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781607801579 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Never trust the wrapper',
        text: "Business is always a gamble. Some weeks the dice roll your way, and other weeks you wonder why you ever walked through the door. When a company catches fire and money starts pouring in, the noise around it makes sense.\n\nWeWork was once one of the most valuable names in the business world. Adam Neumann founded the coworking giant in 2008, and at its peak the company was worth a stunning forty seven billion dollars. Then, in September 2019, the whole thing fell apart. Around forty billion dollars of value evaporated in days, a fall almost no one had ever seen.\n\nInvestors and employees woke up to a nightmare, watching a so-called sure thing collapse in front of them. Neumann, by some strange twist, walked away with most of his fortune. His reputation was a different story.\n\nThe picture that came out was not flattering. Neumann loved the high life, and he spent freely at every chance he got. As history has shown, lavish spending rarely ends with a happy ending.\n\nNeumann had spotted a craving in a new generation. Younger workers were tired of dull, characterless office cubicles, and they wanted a space that felt more like home. WeWork answered that call. The company rented out offices, dressed them up with playful design, and offered perks that rivaled top hotels. Growth came fast.\n\nBy 2019, WeWork was running four hundred and twenty five locations worldwide, and the brand was easy to spot in almost any major city.\n\nAlmost no one saw how much money the company was burning, even the people investing in it. The losses were not the result of a bad plan or a broken model. They were the result of Neumann's appetite for spending. He lived like a king, with a personal net worth near ten billion dollars, seven homes, and a small army of staff that followed him from place to place.\n\nWhere did it all go wrong? This summary walks through the surprising story of WeWork's rise and crash, and the biggest lesson is the old one. Never judge a book by its cover, because the story inside can be far darker than the shine on the dust jacket."
      },
      {
        title: 'Every empire starts with a small seed',
        text: "Adam Neumann was never the type to settle. He was born to Israeli parents in April 1979, and his parents split up when he was seven. He moved to the United States with his mother and sister, though the new life was rough and the family eventually returned to Israel.\n\nBack home, Neumann grew bored with his small town and started dreaming of something bigger. He left mandatory military service, told his sister to pack a bag, and the two of them set off for New York City.\n\nAt twenty seven, Neumann launched a small company called Krawlers, selling baby clothes. The star product was a onesie and pant set with built-in knee pads, designed to help babies crawl. What he did not yet see was the obvious flaw in the plan. Babies crawl for only a few months before they start walking, and the market for kneepads disappears almost overnight.\n\nNew York City was magnetic for Neumann, since the city felt full of open doors. He was drawn to the bright lights and the fast pace.\n\nEven with the rough start, Neumann was making money, and his natural hustle kept him pushing deals with suppliers. New ideas kept landing in his lap, and he floated from gig to gig for a while, even giving modeling a try.\n\nIn the summer of 2005, Neumann met the man who would become his business partner, Miguel McKelvey. Where Neumann was loud and quick, McKelvey was quiet and thoughtful. They batted ideas back and forth and settled on becoming office space providers. The plan was loose, and the details were still missing, until Neumann met Jack Guttman, a landlord with a spare floor. Neumann worked his charm, and Guttman agreed to come along.\n\nAs McKelvey said later, Neumann had a bottomless faith in his ability to talk people into his way of thinking.\n\nOnce Guttman said yes, the partners sketched out the layout and design. Neumann wanted a community feel in the offices, and the early signs were good. MTV rented one of the first spaces. They called the new venture GreenDesk."
      },
      {
        title: 'WeWork caught a shift in how people wanted to work',
        text: "GreenDesk grew stronger, and Neumann started to feel restless. He wanted more, and a small win was never enough. The result was WeWork.\n\nNeumann had noticed a clear shift in the workforce. Millennials were walking into offices for the first time, and they wanted something different. They did not want characterless cubicles. They wanted a social feel, a place that reflected how they saw their work. Neumann set out to build a workspace that felt closer to a college dorm than a corporate floor.\n\nAround this time, Neumann met Rebekah, who would become his wife. Things were lining up, and he started to pitch his WeWork idea. The pitch was bold, but it landed, especially with the early success of GreenDesk behind him.\n\nJoel Schriber, an investor with a sharp eye, decided to write a check, and the pace picked up. GreenDesk was folded into WeWork to fund new space, and Neumann began knocking on doors of real estate agents. Schriber even signed the guarantee on the first lease, though the rent was steep, and Miguel McKelvey had to keep calling Schriber to chase the promised payments. Meanwhile, Rebekah Neumann started shaping the brand's look and feel.\n\nThe first WeWork building, which also served as the company headquarters, opened in the SoHo district of New York City.\n\nSuccess came at a sprint. As Neumann brought on more staff, he handed out stock options, which is common in tech startups. Instead of walking new hires through the business model, he told them how much their shares would be worth once the company hit a five hundred billion dollar valuation. For Neumann, the question was never if, only when.\n\nThe company spread fast through 2012 and 2013, with new spaces in Manhattan, Los Angeles, and San Francisco.\n\nA side note: WeWork rode the wave of remote work and the focus on work life balance, both of which fueled demand for flexible office space."
      },
      {
        title: 'The first cracks showed up in the ethics',
        text: "From day one, Adam Neumann pushed his team hard. He told new hires they would need to make personal sacrifices and work late, sometimes over the weekend. He framed the work as a shared mission, a project the whole company would win together.\n\nBehind the scenes, though, Neumann was cutting deals that lined his own pockets. He had told the company at the start that he would not take a salary, but he soon began pulling large chunks of cash out of the business and moving them straight into his personal accounts. His lifestyle was growing faster than the business, and he needed more and more money to fund it.\n\nMost tech startups, the bucket WeWork was still trying to fit into, did not follow that pattern. The usual rule is that employees and investors start to see gains at the same time. The founder becoming extremely rich before the rest of the team is considered a bad sign.\n\nNot long after WeWork took off, people started asking whether the company was really a tech company or whether it had drifted into real estate.\n\nNeumann began closing deals that made him money from the same buildings WeWork was leasing. He used company cash to fund the investments, and the more successful the deals became, the more he poured in. The conflicts of interest were obvious, and many inside the company worried about how it looked to outside investors. A long list of self dealing deals is a quick way to scare off new money.\n\nNeumann shrugged off the warnings, even from his inner circle, who told him that using WeWork's money to buy real estate was a bad look.\n\nAll the while, his personal life grew louder. He was often spotted at celebrity parties, flashing cash, and buying homes around the world. He enjoyed the perks of being the face of one of the most talked about startups, and his charm often got him out of tight spots. That reputation for antics was starting to follow him."
      },
      {
        title: 'Never spend more than the till can cover',
        text: "Neumann's high cost lifestyle was starting to dent WeWork's books, and it was clear that the company was spending far more than it was bringing in.\n\nMost tech startups start in the red, and after about seven years they either break even or watch the losses shrink. WeWork was moving in the opposite direction. The losses were growing, and yet a lot of people inside the company were looking the other way.\n\nLife was getting harder for startups in Silicon Valley at the time. Many tech companies had boomed in their first years, only to start reporting heavy losses. WeWork looked like the loudest example of the pattern.\n\nThe basic problem was simple. The money chasing companies had grown much faster than the number of strong ideas.\n\nKeen to steady the books, Neumann went looking for fresh investment. The biggest play was a major deal with SoftBank, and the valuation on that deal was about twenty times the company's actual revenue.\n\nAnother move was to start subleasing space to large companies. The plan worked at first, and Amazon became one of WeWork's first big tenants. Still, costs kept climbing, and revenue did not keep up. The growth was moving faster than the cash.\n\nFast growth is not always a gift. A company that scales too quickly often loses control of quality.\n\nNeumann refused to admit the problem. He did not want to spell out the need for more money, since that would dent the optimistic story. He also refused to share the company's actual numbers, even though full disclosure could have attracted new investors. The trouble was that the numbers, once shown, would scare most investors off.\n\nThe SoftBank deal fell through, which was a heavy blow. Neumann's inner circle started pushing him to open the books and go public. They needed cash, and they needed it soon."
      },
      {
        title: 'The WeWork collapse sent shockwaves around the world',
        text: "Almost no one outside Neumann's inner circle knew the trouble WeWork was in. Neumann himself was still in denial, and he kept up the party lifestyle, traveling with celebrity friends and investing in their side projects, including a company tied to Ashton Kutcher.\n\nAt the January 2019 WeWork Global Summit, Neumann looked worn out. His usual energy was nowhere to be seen, and the strain of the failed SoftBank deal was visible.\n\nWeWork's spending was far above its revenue. In 2018, spending hit an estimated three and a half billion dollars, while revenue sat at one and a half billion.\n\nThe board decided that going public was the best shot at fresh capital. The plan meant filing for an Initial Public Offering, an IPO, which lets public investors buy shares and pour money into the company. To go public, the company had to file a handbook for potential investors, which laid out what the company was and how it was run. The handbook became a problem.\n\nEven after nine years in business, WeWork still could not say clearly what it was. The numbers were hard to present, and the back office looked messy. Investors grew nervous, and the argument over tech startup versus real estate firm kept getting louder.\n\nAt the same time, stories about WeWork's corporate governance started to leak. Public valuation began to slide, the drop was small at first, and then the bottom fell out.\n\nThe board started asking harder questions. Neumann's long spell of charm was wearing off, and he could feel a coup forming. Pressure to step down kept building.\n\nThe company's valuation crashed to a record low, and Neumann was pushed out as CEO. SoftBank bought the company at a steep discount in March 2020. In the thirty three days after the IPO filing, WeWork's value dropped by seventy percent, and investors lost a fortune.\n\nAdam Neumann's charm could not save him from a failure of that scale."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "No business is safe from failure, and even a strong idea can collapse under poor leadership. A solid foundation and steady hands at the top make success far more likely.\n\nWeWork had a great idea and a workable model, but the leadership and the back office let it down. Instead of pouring cash into the business and building for the long haul, Adam Neumann chased a fast and lavish life. Celebrity parties, exotic vacations, multiple homes, and heavy spending are expensive hobbies, and they were funded by money pulled out of the company.\n\nThe core idea was sound. Millennials care a lot more about work life balance than earlier generations, and coworking spaces are perfect for remote workers and small teams that want a more social workplace. So the concept was never the problem. The problem was the way the company was run. Was it a tech startup, or was it a real estate operation with shaky leadership, as so many suspected?\n\nMany investors lost a lot of money when WeWork collapsed, and many employees lost their jobs. As of 2022, Adam Neumann's personal net worth was about one and a half billion dollars. For such a stunning fall from grace, Neumann still managed to land on his feet, while the people who worked with and for him paid the highest price.\n\nTry this. In business and in your own finances, it pays to spend less than you earn, so build a budget and stick to it. Living large feels exciting, but it often leads to burnout, so leave room for the quieter moments. If you have a business idea, follow the plan and watch your cash flow closely.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-culture-map.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-culture-map', title: 'The Culture Map', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781606358554 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Cracking the code for working across cultures',
        text: "Communication is the foundation of every business. The tools change as civilization moves forward, but the basic rule does not. The receiver has to understand the message, or the conversation fails. Inside one country, communication usually feels easy. Cross a border, and the task becomes harder. You need a different set of skills to make sure the person across the table reads your message the way you meant it.\n\nStrong teamwork cuts down on cross cultural mistakes, and that lifts the whole operation.\n\nReal understanding of a culture usually comes from time spent there. Living, working, or traveling for months is the best way to pick up the small cues that textbooks miss. Even so, learning a new culture without a clear path is tough.\n\nErin Meyer, a professor who has spent years studying international business, built a set of tools to help decode different societies. The tools are called the Eight Scales. This summary walks through each one.\n\nA quick note. The facts in this summary come from Erin Meyer's own research and observations."
      },
      {
        title: 'A map of the cultural landscape',
        text: "Eight scales show how cultures differ. Used as a guide, they help you read a new society and predict how people will react.\n\nThe first scale is Communicating, which runs from high context to low context. The second is Evaluating, which compares indirect negative feedback with direct negative feedback. The third is Persuading, which compares applications first reasoning with principles first reasoning. The fourth is Leading, which ranges from hierarchical to egalitarian. The fifth is Deciding, which ranges from top down to consensual. The sixth is Trusting, which compares relationship based trust with task based trust. The seventh is Disagreeing, which compares cultures that avoid confrontation with cultures that welcome it. The eighth is Scheduling, which ranges from flexible time to linear time.\n\nWelcoming cultural differences makes your work with people from other backgrounds richer.\n\nThe communication style a culture prefers varies a lot. Many cultures in the United States and other Anglo Saxon countries value open and direct speech as the most effective form. In Asian cultures like India, China, Japan, and Indonesia, communication is softer and richer in meaning, and listeners are expected to read the message from the context. The art is in the nuance.\n\nLanguage is a good hint about the style a culture uses. Japanese and Hindi spoken in New Delhi are high context languages, where a word can carry several meanings depending on the moment. The Japanese word Ashi, for example, can mean leg or foot, depending on context. French is another high context language.\n\nDoing business in a high context world can be tricky if you come from a low context culture and you are not used to words that mean more than one thing. The rest of this summary explains how to move between the two.\n\nThe culture you grow up in shapes how you see the world.\n\nA small note. Japan is an island country surrounded by the Pacific Ocean, the Sea of Okhotsk, the Sea of Japan, and the East China Sea. Its island geography made foreign invasion rare in ancient times."
      },
      {
        title: 'Moving between high and low context',
        text: "French, Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese are Latin Romance languages with a higher context than English, though they sit lower on the scale than most Asian languages.\n\nJapan has the highest context culture in the world, and the United States has the lowest. European countries like Spain, Italy, Mexico, France, Argentina, and Brazil fall somewhere in the middle, and Brazil has the lowest context culture of that group.\n\nListen for the context and the speaker's tone, and you will understand more.\n\nLanguage and shared history are the two biggest factors that decide where a culture lands on the communication scale. High context cultures have long intertwined histories, passed down through generations, and the shared knowledge gives the community a deep, unspoken understanding. That bond is part of what holds the group together.\n\nAs civilization grew, people began to travel, mix with foreigners, and learn about other ways of life. The United States, for example, was built on a steady flow of immigrants from many countries. Those immigrants brought their own histories, languages, and customs, which made the US the most linguistically and culturally diverse country in the world. The US also has one of the shortest shared histories.\n\nWith so much diversity, Americans have learned to spell out their messages as clearly as possible, leaving little room for confusion. That habit helped push the US to the very bottom of the context scale. Singapore and India are other examples of low context cultures shaped by high diversity.\n\nListen before you speak, and learn before you act."
      },
      {
        title: 'How culture shapes persuasion and feedback',
        text: "On the evaluating scale, there are two kinds of negative feedback. The first is direct, and the second is indirect. The kind you should give depends on what the receiver is used to, not on what feels right to you.\n\nIn the Netherlands, the Dutch give very direct feedback, and they aim to be honest and polite at the same time. Hand the same feedback to someone from a culture that prefers indirect talk, though, and the same words can feel rude, insulting, or even offensive.\n\nFeedback is delicate work, and the wrong tone can damage a relationship. The safe move is to learn the culture you are dealing with and shape your feedback to fit.\n\nThe persuading scale is the next piece. Persuasion matters in business, and your cultural background shapes both the way you argue and the kinds of evidence that move you.\n\nAdjust your style to honor the local norm, and the room stays welcoming.\n\nThere are two main ways to reason. The first, called principles first, is also known as deductive reasoning. You start with a general idea and work down to a specific case. If all copper and iron conduct electricity, then the iron chair in your room can conduct electricity too.\n\nThe second, called applications first, is also known as inductive reasoning. You start with a set of observations and work up to a general rule. If every iron chair you have tested conducts electricity, then all iron chairs probably conduct electricity.\n\nMost people can use both styles, and the mix you reach for depends on your cultural background. Embracing different styles can open the door to new ideas in a team setting.\n\nAnglo Saxon cultures, including the UK, the US, New Zealand, Australia, and Canada, lean applications first. Latin American, French, and Germanic cultures tend to lean principles first."
      },
      {
        title: 'Trust across borders',
        text: "There are two kinds of trust. The first is cognitive, and the second is affective.\n\nCognitive trust is the confidence you build in another person based on their work, their skills, and their reliability. You trust them because you have seen them deliver, again and again.\n\nAffective trust grows from emotional ties. It shows up in closeness, empathy, and the warmth of a personal bond.\n\nPractice flexibility and empathy, and you will go further in a global workplace.\n\nFriendships and family bonds are usually built on affective trust. In business, the source of trust shifts as you cross borders.\n\nFor Americans, mixing the two kinds of trust in business feels unprofessional. Chinese managers often blend them, weaving personal relationships with business deals as a single practice. In places like the United States or Switzerland, the saying is that business is business. In places like China or Brazil, the saying is that business is personal.\n\nRussia and India are examples of relationship based cultures, where trust grows from the personal bond. In the United States, trust is more often task based, built on what someone can do rather than who they know.\n\nBuilding trust across cultures is a long game. Once a real rapport is in place, the small misunderstandings are easier to clear up, and the working relationship gets stronger. That is why investing in trust pays off when you do business across borders."
      },
      {
        title: 'Go past the deal',
        text: "When you work with people from a relationship based culture, showing your personality matters. If your hosts value relationships over tasks, try inviting them for a meal.\n\nRemember, a trusting relationship is the foundation of smooth collaboration.\n\nKeep the meal personal. Talk about life, not work, and let the conversation breathe. A relaxed lunch is time well spent. In cultures that prize tasks over relationships, keep the meal short, and do not be offended if some guests show up late, leave early, or skip the invite.\n\nPick a form of communication that fits the culture. With a group that values relationships, a phone call is worth the extra effort, since voice carries warmth in a way an email cannot. Once a strong trust is in place, you can shift back to email and other task focused tools.\n\nThe disagreement scale is the next one. It sorts cultures into two groups. The first group, which includes the Netherlands, Italy, and Spain, treats open disagreement as normal, even healthy. The second group, which includes Sweden, Brazil, the Philippines, and the UK, prefers to keep disagreement out of the open.\n\nA small note. Scandinavia, the United States, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and Australia use first names in emails, while most hierarchical countries still reach for last names."
      },
      {
        title: 'When time tells a different story',
        text: "Time is a powerful force, and none of us can stop it. That is why using it well matters so much.\n\nTime management means planning the day and staying flexible when plans slip. What counts as late in one culture can be on time in another. People tend to live in either flexible time cultures or linear time cultures. In a flexible time culture, a set time is a guide rather than a rule, since many things can go wrong and cause a delay. In a linear time culture, a set time is a set time.\n\nRespect the way other cultures handle time, and communication gets easier.\n\nDeveloped countries often live in linear time, since their systems are reliable. They can plan activities days or weeks ahead, knowing the weather and the traffic will not surprise them.\n\nThe story is different in developing nations like Nigeria, where life is shaped by constant change. Systems fail, traffic is unpredictable, and rules can shift overnight. People who succeed in these settings learn to roll with the punches, which is the heart of flexible time.\n\nLinear time shows up most in Germany, Anglo Saxon countries, and Northern Europe. Latin and many African cultures lean toward flexible time. Asian cultures cover a wide range, with Japan leaning linear, and China and India leaning flexible.\n\nA small note. Germany industrialized early, in part because it has a reliable structure and a linear time culture."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "The eight scales in this summary point to the things you most need to know about the cultures you work with.\n\nYou can sharpen your relationships and your business by paying attention to where you and your partners land on each scale. A cultural map is a quick way to line up the differences inside a team.\n\nSpotting the similarities and the differences helps you see where disagreements might pop up. Welcoming the richness of different cultures lets you act as a bridge, helping your team grow more adaptable. That kind of work builds a calm, inclusive space, and it lifts collaboration and mutual understanding for everyone.\n\nTry this. Make a short list of five or six people you trust. They can come from different parts of your life, such as parents, a partner, a business ally, or a long time client. Reflect on the moments that built that trust, and pull out the lessons you can use elsewhere. Use the eight scales to map the cultures of the people you work with, and watch the picture come into focus.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-death-of-expertise.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-death-of-expertise', title: 'The Death of Expertise', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781607254749 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A sugar free expertise, please',
        text: "A few decades ago, you did not have to read the news with a magnifying glass. People trusted the press, and the press traded on that trust. The world has changed in surprising ways since then, and so has the media. Online outlets, journals, YouTube channels, and traditional TV stations all compete for the same eyes. Even television has bent toward the broadest audience it can find, and not every change has been kind.\n\nIf the world is your oyster, do not let the media serve it on the plate for you.\n\nToday's news outlets and experts have a long road back to trust, and the road starts in the classroom. Colleges and universities still shape how people learn to weigh an argument, and the lessons there spill out into the workplace and the living room.\n\nMedia has become a kind of diet, and like every diet, it has rules. So hop in the imaginary car, because it is time to shop for a healthier media menu."
      },
      {
        title: 'To err is human',
        text: "We all know someone who questions everything and offers advice you did not ask for. Lately, that attitude has spread. More people show open hostility toward experts, because experts point out an awkward truth about American life, which is that not everyone is an expert. In a democracy, every opinion is treated as equal, and the line between a hobbyist and a trained professional starts to blur. Misinformation spreads, and the internet pours gasoline on the fire.\n\nAlexis de Tocqueville, a French thinker, traced American skepticism of experts to the country's deep individualism, where personal opinion often trumps outside authority.\n\nHierarchy is not all bad. It can show you ways to grow.\n\nThe push for self reliance came with a price. When people realized how much work it takes to master a complex subject, whether plumbing or running a small business, frustration grew, and that frustration often turned on the experts. Richard Hofstadter, a political scientist, made the point in 1963 that learning how complicated the world really is can leave people feeling helpless, and that helplessness often curdles into anger at the people who do understand. Knowing a fact and understanding what it means are two different things.\n\nSo what makes someone an expert? The short answer is steady practice, which would also make your mail carrier an expert at delivering mail. The longer answer needs a bit more nuance. A trustworthy expert usually shows four traits. They have talent and a real passion for the work, since no school can light that fire for them. They keep learning, exploring new areas and turning past mistakes into lessons. They have years of hands on experience, which builds instincts that no book can teach. And they welcome regular feedback from peers, since that keeps their work honest and current.\n\nA quick word on mistakes. Self styled coach experts love to pounce when a real professional gets a call wrong. Yes, everyone slips sometimes, but the weight of right calls versus wrong calls is what matters, and on that score, trained experts are right far more often than the average person. Listening to a specialist does not erase error, but it shrinks the odds of one.\n\nThe intellectual was once gently mocked for being unneeded. Now the intellectual is fiercely resented for being needed too much."
      },
      {
        title: 'I know that I know nothing',
        text: "Have you ever tried to argue with someone who clearly does not know the subject, and felt your blood pressure climb? On the surface, the answer is simple, since common sense should be enough. Underneath, there is research that explains why the argument feels hopeless.\n\nPeople with less information often act more confident than they are, while people with more information tend to second guess themselves. Psychologists call this the Dunning Kruger effect. The less you know, the harder it is to see how deep the topic goes, so you overestimate yourself. The more you know, the more you weigh the small details, so you slow down.\n\nThe sting of knowing too much is still better than the comfort of not knowing.\n\nAnother piece of the puzzle is metacognition, which is the habit of stepping back to look at your own thinking. A trained musician hears a wrong note in their own playing, while a less trained peer may think the playing sounds fine. The skill of catching your own mistakes takes practice.\n\nDavid Dunning, one of the researchers behind the Dunning Kruger effect, points out that people often weigh in on topics they barely understand. Our brains evolved to fit in with the group, which can hide our blind spots from us. The result is a confident critic who has no idea how much they do not know, and they think they know plenty.\n\nThat critic is also the hardest person to convince, since they tend to pick facts that match what they already believe. Psychologists call this confirmation bias. Try convincing someone who is afraid of flying to board a plane, and they will list every crash they have ever heard of, no matter how rare.\n\nNo one is free of bias, not even the experts. In 2014, a graduate student faked the results of a study claiming that gay people could change homophobic attitudes about gay marriage. A senior professor endorsed the work, later admitting that they wanted the findings to be true, and that hope made them miss the fraud.\n\nThe fix is a principle called Occam's Razor, which says to pick the simplest explanation that fits the facts. Walking away from the self styled expert is also a fine choice, since you cannot win an argument with a wall."
      },
      {
        title: 'Why are students skipping the work',
        text: "When did higher education lose its shine? Today, going to college no longer carries the same weight it once did. Telling a friend you applied to college can earn you a raised eyebrow, and the question is fair. What made the old model of higher learning feel less special?\n\nA few forces are at work. A century ago, only a small slice of young people went to college, and a diploma stood out. Now that more families can afford it, the diploma is far more common. On top of that, universities have become a way to fill the gap between high school and a first job.\n\nLife has grown more stressful over the decades, and young people look for a soft place to land. Many parents are happy to help, with helicopter parenting showing up in moves like relocating near a child's campus or helping with homework. That kind of help can get in the way of basic life skills, including critical thinking, which is the habit of weighing new information on its merits.\n\nGood education grows from a hunger to learn and from respect for the people who can teach.\n\nParents are not the only ones in the story. The colleges themselves carry a share of the blame. Many institutions seem built for self preservation, opening more programs to chase more applicants in the name of giving everyone a college experience.\n\nA flood of new programs does not guarantee quality. Some teachers who came up through small, underfunded local colleges may not have the tools they need, and even a dedicated professor can burn out when students do not show up ready to work.\n\nStudents sometimes treat higher education like a service, and teachers like service providers, rather than guides with hard won knowledge. The result is a stream of graduates with a thin grasp of what they supposedly studied.\n\nA 2014 study found that liberals are more likely to block or unfriend people they disagree with online. Conservatives, by contrast, were less likely to befriend those people in the first place."
      },
      {
        title: 'Is no opinion better than a wrong one',
        text: "What is the first thing you do when you do not know something? You Google it. The dark joke about the web is that it hands you a mountain of information but very little judgment to sort it. In a strange twist, knowing more can leave you less sharp, so should you really try to know it all?\n\nThe web would be safer if every browser came with a banner that read, Ninety percent of what you see here is not accurate. That rule is called Sturgeon's Law, named after the science fiction writer Theodore Sturgeon, who used the line in many of his critiques. Most users assume that the first answer on the page is true, and that assumption is one of the quietest frauds the internet commits on the brain.\n\nThe web has flattened the way people process information, and what used to be careful research has shrunk to a quick scan of the first few pages of results. Apply Sturgeon's Law to that scan, and the answer is obvious.\n\nBeing reckless online is a new kind of liquid courage, and both leave you with a headache.\n\nA second problem hides in plain sight. Browsers do not really weigh whether a result is true, false, or unverified, so the internet starts to look all knowing, and that image chips away at the value of a real expert. Why call a specialist when the answer is one search away?\n\nThe web's veil of anonymity also flattens the difference between a trained expert and a self styled one, and the trained expert usually pays the price. A famous specialist with a social media account can sound just as confident as a hobbyist, and that false confidence gives voice to people who do not know the full picture.\n\nWikipedia is the most famous attempt at a crowd built encyclopedia, and its struggle to keep quality high shows how hard it is to keep a crowd honest. Even with some well protected corners, Wikipedia is fairly easy for unverified editors to slip into.\n\nThe real fix is for people to relearn how to research and to think critically. That kind of change is bigger than any one of us, and even Google cannot answer how to make it happen."
      },
      {
        title: 'The end of journalism',
        text: "One pattern in this generation troubles a long list of specialists. They doubt almost everything, and the headlines rank high on the list. Younger readers hesitate to trust even the most established outlets, and they sound adrift, smothered by a fog of self defensive cynicism.\n\nA dash of careful doubt is fine, and it actually sharpens how we weigh an argument. Once that doubt starts to spread like a virus, the natural question is what is feeding it. From the postwar era forward, the number of outlets has ballooned, and each one battles for the next click, even when the fight drags them toward spectacle over substance.\n\nOld radio, broadcast TV, and the modern web have all hooked the public through debates, commentary, and recommendations. That pull has chained the human mind to a torrent of headlines and ads, and it has frayed the craft of the reporter. The constant flood of information dulls the brain until it can no longer absorb or weigh the news, and people either pick up nothing or surrender the wish to learn.\n\nAudiences once leaned on the press for fresh knowledge. Now the press leans on audiences to keep itself alive.\n\nThis tilt cuts deepest among students, who seem more distracted and emotionally flat as the number of outlets keeps climbing. Even the people producing the news acknowledge that pushing so much urgency at once leaves the reader befuddled and spent. A 2011 study from the University of Chicago found that college graduates seldom apply careful thought to civic and social questions, and the reason is straightforward, since they have stopped caring about them.\n\nThe scramble for viewers has bent the very idea of journalism toward something closer to content production. More outlets bring more rivalry, more niches, and more writers, including those with shaky skills. The end product is a media world that feeds readers fast food headlines rather than the slower information they need in order to reflect.\n\nThe rise of fresh platforms and the fall in trust are both tied to the slow death of expertise."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "In a world saturated with ads and headlines, each person becomes their own fact checker, tutor, and guide. Learning to sort what you want and need to hear is a kind of wisdom that older generations did not have to build.\n\nSince headlines are turning into content, shaping how you see the world now rests in your hands, rather than being handed off by a handful of state run outlets. There is always a pick between the red pill and the blue pill, and the real work is learning to tell them apart, along with every shade in between.\n\nTry this. Before you take in a new idea and form a view, take for granted that the writer has more background than you. Add some variety to your reading by opening an outlet that you would normally skip, or by reading something you disagree with. Reporters slip up too, and a little patience goes a long way, since they are doing their best, like any other specialist.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  }
};
